-- `@ once` on a closure parameter is a type-level usage contract: the callee may
-- call it at most once, and only directly. The fact is erased before Core (it
-- constrains checking, not execution), so an accepted program runs identically on
-- both backends and threads no differently from an unannotated closure.
fn once_apply(g : ((Int) -> Int) @ once, x : Int) : Int = g(x)

-- A `@ once` closure may be handed on to another `@ once` parameter (a single
-- delegated use), and the compiler tracks that this is still at most one call.
fn relay(g : ((Int) -> Int) @ once, x : Int) : Int = once_apply(g, x)

fn main() =
  println(once_apply(\(n) -> n * 2, 21))
  println(relay(\(n) -> n + 100, 5))
